    {
        "content": "<p><code>by</code> puts you in tactic mode, so it sort of depends on whether you want to be in tactic mode. Being in tactic mode just means that the stuff after <code>by</code> will be parsed and elaborated differently than it would be sans <code>out</code>. I guess <code>calc</code> has both a term and a tactic parser so you don't strictly need the <code>by</code>.</p>",
        "id": 465025081,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Bailey",
        "timestamp": 1724601299
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, I think we should not confuse beginners by talking about tactic mode and just use <code>by</code> consistently in materials for them</p>",
        "id": 465026744,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1724603057
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"307953\">Ruben Van de Velde</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/113489-new-members/topic/good.20habit.20to.20use.20.60.3A.3D.20by.60.20at.20end.20of.20first.20proof.20header.20line.3F/near/465026744\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yeah, I think we should not confuse beginners by talking about tactic mode and just use <code>by</code> consistently in materials for them</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Amen to that :)</p>\n<p>I will update my beginner tutorials to include <code>by</code>.</p>\n<p>I ran into the issue today as I develop the next example code which uses <code>obtain</code> not <code>calc</code> for the first time.</p>",
